\begin{equation*}R_{0}=0.211[{\kappa}^{2}n^{-4}Q_{{\mathrm{D}}}J({\lambda})]^{1/6},\end{equation*}\end{document}where κ2 is the relative orientational factor between dipoles, n is the refractive index of the medium, QD is the quantum yield of the donor, and the numerical factor combines unit conversion factors (57). κ2 can vary between 0–4 and we used the standard approach of taking κ2 = 2/3, which is the motion-averaged value. For the refractive index of a vesicle suspension the value of n = 1.4 was used (57). The quantum yield of MB is QD = 0.89 (58), and the extinction coefficient of NBD-POPE at 463 nm is ɛA = 21,000 M−1 cm−1 (59). The calculated Förster distance was R0 = 46 Å. For reference, we determined ɛA = 24,000 M−1 cm−1 for MB-POPE at 368 nm (absorption maximum) under basic conditions (methanol/∼50 mM KOH).

Since a lipid has a diameter of ∼8 Å, the experimentally determined R0 = 46 Å corresponds to a circle with a radius of ∼6 lipids (Fig. 2). The energy transfer efficiency, \documentclass[10pt]{article}
